{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UkWw98uRLriVuYNXTMBubh","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# QA Backtest Report — T570\n2\t\n3\t**Validator:** Tina (QA Engineer)\n4\t**Date:** 2026-04-04\n5\t**Target:** Dave's `output/dave/backtest_results.json` (T568)\n6\t**Reference:** Bob's `output/bob/trade_signals.json` (T555/T567)\n7\t**Culture refs:** Following C8 (verify code), C11 (review), D5 (runnable system)\n8\t\n9\t## Verdict: FAIL — 5 Critical Issues Found\n10\t\n11\t| Category | PASS | FAIL | WARN |\n12\t|----------|------|------|------|\n13\t| Signal Count | 0 | 1 | 0 |\n14\t| P&L Math | 7 | 14 | 0 |\n15\t| Drawdown | 0 | 14 | 0 |\n16\t| Data Leakage | 1 | 0 | 19 |\n17\t| Config | 4 | 0 | 0 |\n18\t| **Total** | **12** | **29** | **19** |\n19\t\n20\t---\n21\t\n22\t## Critical Finding 1: Duplicate Trades (BUG)\n23\t\n24\t4 pairs of identical trades detected in the BTC/ETH pair:\n25\t\n26\t| Trade A | Trade B | entryZ | exitZ | netPnl |\n27\t|---------|---------|--------|-------|--------|\n28\t| trade_2 | trade_3 | -2.188 | -0.197 | $1.911 |\n29\t| trade_7 | trade_8 | 1.614 | 0.48 | $1.054 |\n30\t| trade_9 | trade_10 | 1.385 | -0.014 | $1.291 |\n31\t| trade_16 | trade_17 | 1.656 | 0.451 | $1.125 |\n32\t\n33\t**Impact:** These duplicates inflate the BTC/ETH pair's win count (8 wins, but 4 are duplicates) and P&L by ~$5.38. The 61.1% win rate drops to ~50% if duplicates are removed.\n34\t\n35\t**Root cause:** Likely the same BTC/ETH pair appearing in two different clusters (`crypto_internal` and `crypto_macro` in Bob's signals), causing the backtester to process the same trade twice.\n36\t\n37\t## Critical Finding 2: Anomalous Z-Score (trade_1)\n38\t\n39\t- `trade_1` has `entryZ: 40, exitZ: 40` — a z-score of 40 is statistically impossible (~10^-350 probability)\n40\t- This looks like a sentinel/default value, not a real z-score\n41\t- The trade correctly shows 0 improvement and -$0.12 loss (fees only)\n42\t- **Risk:** If this represents uninitialized data, other trades may have subtle data integrity issues\n43\t\n44\t## Critical Finding 3: P&L Model Is Not Spread-Based\n45\t\n46\tDave uses: `rawPnl = zImprovement * $0.50/contract/z-point * contracts`\n47\t\n48\tThis is a **synthetic P&L model** that estimates profit from z-score improvement, NOT from actual spread changes. While creative, this has problems:\n49\t- The $0.50/z-point conversion factor is arbitrary — no calibration against real Kalshi spreads\n50\t- P&L numbers ($14.26 total, 14.14% return) are **not reflective of real trading economics**\n51\t- For Kalshi binary contracts ($0-$1 range), a z-score-based model overstates returns\n52\t\n53\tBob's signal data includes actual `entry_spread` and `exit_spread` values, which should be used for P&L calculation. The spread-based P&L would likely show much smaller (and more realistic) returns.\n54\t\n55\t## Critical Finding 4: Signal Count Mismatch\n56\t\n57\t- Bob's current `trade_signals.json`: **47 signals**\n58\t- Dave's backtest consumed: **38 signals** (from an earlier version)\n59\t- 9 signals were added after Dave started his backtest\n60\t\n61\t**Impact:** The backtest doesn't cover all available signals. This isn't necessarily wrong (Dave used the data available at time of run), but the results are not comprehensive.\n62\t\n63\t## Critical Finding 5: No Walk-Forward / Out-of-Sample Testing\n64\t\n65\t- No train/test split detected in the methodology\n66\t- The backtest generates and tests signals on the same price history\n67\t- **Risk:** Overfitting — the strategy may look profitable on historical data but fail on new data\n68\t- **Recommendation:** Implement walk-forward validation (70/30 train/test split as Bob's backtest_signals.js does)\n69\t\n70\t## Minor Issues\n71\t\n72\t1. **No timestamps on trades** — cannot verify temporal ordering or data leakage through time\n73\t2. **Drawdown tracking discrepancy** — reported 1.92%, my independent calculation differs (likely due to the duplicate trade issue distorting capital progression)\n74\t3. **Capital progression errors** — 13 of 18 trades show small discrepancies in `capitalAfter`, likely from cumulative floating-point drift caused by duplicates\n75\t\n76\t## What Passes\n77\t\n78\t- Config consistency (maxDrawdownPct, initialCapital, tradingFee match)\n79\t- Win count matches trade data (11 wins)\n80\t- Win rate (61.1%) matches\n81\t- Summary P&L is consistent with sum of individual trades\n82\t- 5 of 18 trades have correct spread-based P&L\n83\t\n84\t## Bob's Signal Data Summary\n85\t\n86\t- Total signals: 47 (updated from 38)\n87\t- Strategy: z_score_mean_reversion\n88\t- Config: z_entry=1.2, z_exit=0.5, z_stop=3.0\n89\t- Pairs: 6 correlation pairs, 3 arbitrage opportunities\n90\t\n91\t## Recommendations\n92\t\n93\t1. **Fix duplicate trade bug** — deduplicate signals by market pair before backtesting (ignore cluster assignment for same pair)\n94\t2. **Fix z=40 anomaly** — add z-score bounds check (reject |z| > 10 as data error)\n95\t3. **Use spread-based P&L** — calculate P&L from actual spread changes, not z-score improvement\n96\t4. **Add walk-forward testing** — train on 70% of history, test on remaining 30%\n97\t5. **Add timestamps** — enable temporal ordering verification\n98\t6. **Re-run on latest signals** — Bob now has 47 signals vs 38 used\n99\t\n100\t## Runnable Artifact\n101\t\n102\t```bash\n103\tcd agents/tina/output && node qa_backtest_validator.js\n104\t```\n105\t\n106\t---\n107\t*Generated by qa_backtest_validator.js (T570) — Tina, QA Engineer*\n108\t*Run: `node qa_backtest_validator.js [path_to_backtest_results.json]`*\n109\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ade42b78-5405-44ee-8473-f8242c3fe738","uuid":"bbe7da6c-a197-4e5b-a2e5-43e6bbf9e895","timestamp":"2026-04-04T07:51:08.044Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/chenyangcui/Documents/code/aicompany/planets/kalshi-traders/agents/tina/output/qa_backtest_report.md","content":"# QA Backtest Report — T570\n\n**Validator:** Tina (QA Engineer)\n**Date:** 2026-04-04\n**Target:** Dave's `output/dave/backtest_results.json` (T568)\n**Reference:** Bob's `output/bob/trade_signals.json` (T555/T567)\n**Culture refs:** Following C8 (verify code), C11 (review), D5 (runnable system)\n\n## Verdict: FAIL — 5 Critical Issues Found\n\n| Category | PASS | FAIL | WARN |\n|----------|------|------|------|\n| Signal Count | 0 | 1 | 0 |\n| P&L Math | 7 | 14 | 0 |\n| Drawdown | 0 | 14 | 0 |\n| Data Leakage | 1 | 0 | 19 |\n| Config | 4 | 0 | 0 |\n| **Total** | **12** | **29** | **19** |\n\n---\n\n## Critical Finding 1: Duplicate Trades (BUG)\n\n4 pairs of identical trades detected in the BTC/ETH pair:\n\n| Trade A | Trade B | entryZ | exitZ | netPnl |\n|---------|---------|--------|-------|--------|\n| trade_2 | trade_3 | -2.188 | -0.197 | $1.911 |\n| trade_7 | trade_8 | 1.614 | 0.48 | $1.054 |\n| trade_9 | trade_10 | 1.385 | -0.014 | $1.291 |\n| trade_16 | trade_17 | 1.656 | 0.451 | $1.125 |\n\n**Impact:** These duplicates inflate the BTC/ETH pair's win count (8 wins, but 4 are duplicates) and P&L by ~$5.38. The 61.1% win rate drops to ~50% if duplicates are removed.\n\n**Root cause:** Likely the same BTC/ETH pair appearing in two different clusters (`crypto_internal` and `crypto_macro` in Bob's signals), causing the backtester to process the same trade twice.\n\n## Critical Finding 2: Anomalous Z-Score (trade_1)\n\n- `trade_1` has `entryZ: 40, exitZ: 40` — a z-score of 40 is statistically impossible (~10^-350 probability)\n- This looks like a sentinel/default value, not a real z-score\n- The trade correctly shows 0 improvement and -$0.12 loss (fees only)\n- **Risk:** If this represents uninitialized data, other trades may have subtle data integrity issues\n\n## Critical Finding 3: P&L Model Is Not Spread-Based\n\nDave uses: `rawPnl = zImprovement * $0.50/contract/z-point * contracts`\n\nThis is a **synthetic P&L model** that estimates profit from z-score improvement, NOT from actual spread changes. While creative, this has problems:\n- The $0.50/z-point conversion factor is arbitrary — no calibration against real Kalshi spreads\n- P&L numbers ($14.26 total, 14.14% return) are **not reflective of real trading economics**\n- For Kalshi binary contracts ($0-$1 range), a z-score-based model overstates returns\n\nBob's signal data includes actual `entry_spread` and `exit_spread` values, which should be used for P&L calculation. The spread-based P&L would likely show much smaller (and more realistic) returns.\n\n## Critical Finding 4: Signal Count Mismatch\n\n- Bob's current `trade_signals.json`: **47 signals**\n- Dave's backtest consumed: **38 signals** (from an earlier version)\n- 9 signals were added after Dave started his backtest\n\n**Impact:** The backtest doesn't cover all available signals. This isn't necessarily wrong (Dave used the data available at time of run), but the results are not comprehensive.\n\n## Critical Finding 5: No Walk-Forward / Out-of-Sample Testing\n\n- No train/test split detected in the methodology\n- The backtest generates and tests signals on the same price history\n- **Risk:** Overfitting — the strategy may look profitable on historical data but fail on new data\n- **Recommendation:** Implement walk-forward validation (70/30 train/test split as Bob's backtest_signals.js does)\n\n## Minor Issues\n\n1. **No timestamps on trades** — cannot verify temporal ordering or data leakage through time\n2. **Drawdown tracking discrepancy** — reported 1.92%, my independent calculation differs (likely due to the duplicate trade issue distorting capital progression)\n3. **Capital progression errors** — 13 of 18 trades show small discrepancies in `capitalAfter`, likely from cumulative floating-point drift caused by duplicates\n\n## What Passes\n\n- Config consistency (maxDrawdownPct, initialCapital, tradingFee match)\n- Win count matches trade data (11 wins)\n- Win rate (61.1%) matches\n- Summary P&L is consistent with sum of individual trades\n- 5 of 18 trades have correct spread-based P&L\n\n## Bob's Signal Data Summary\n\n- Total signals: 47 (updated from 38)\n- Strategy: z_score_mean_reversion\n- Config: z_entry=1.2, z_exit=0.5, z_stop=3.0\n- Pairs: 6 correlation pairs, 3 arbitrage opportunities\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **Fix duplicate trade bug** — deduplicate signals by market pair before backtesting (ignore cluster assignment for same pair)\n2. **Fix z=40 anomaly** — add z-score bounds check (reject |z| > 10 as data error)\n3. **Use spread-based P&L** — calculate P&L from actual spread changes, not z-score improvement\n4. **Add walk-forward testing** — train on 70% of history, test on remaining 30%\n5. **Add timestamps** — enable temporal ordering verification\n6. **Re-run on latest signals** — Bob now has 47 signals vs 38 used\n\n## Runnable Artifact\n\n```bash\ncd agents/tina/output && node qa_backtest_validator.js\n```\n\n---\n*Generated by qa_backtest_validator.js (T570) — Tina, QA Engineer*\n*Run: `node qa_backtest_validator.js [path_to_backtest_results.json]`*\n","numLines":109,"startLine":1,"totalLines":109}}}
